JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand traded firmer on Monday, shrugging off a credit downgrade of both local and foreign currency ratings as investors kept faith in the high yield on offer.At 0650 GMT, the rand traded 0.62% firmer at 12.8675 per dollar compared to close of 12.9475 on Friday in New York.Moody&#8217;s on Friday lowered South Africa&#8217;s rating by a single notch from Baa2 to Baa3, the bottom of the investment grade table with a negative outlook, citing a recent abrupt cabinet reshuffle and reduced growth prospects.Read: SA escapes junk rating as Moody s cuts by one stepThere is uncertainty in developed market currencies following last week&#8217;s UK election, upcoming Federal Reserve interest rates decision, aided inflows into emerging markets.Bonds were also firmer, with yield on benchmark 2026 government bond down 1 basis point to 8.48%.Stocks set to open lower at 0700 GMT, with the JSE securities exchange&#8217;s Top-40 futures index down 0.66%. 